Using hint 2, we can set up a system of equations:

\begin{align*}
p &= bp - bc/a \\
q &= bq - bc/a
\end{align*}

Subtracting the second equation from the first, we get:

\begin{align*}
p-q &= b(p-q) - bc/a \\
-2k\pi &\leq p-q \leq 2k\pi & \text{where } k \in \mathbb{Z} \\
0 &\leq |p-q| \leq 4k\pi & \text{since } b > 0
\end{align*}

To minimize $|p-q|$, we want to maximize $k$. So, we set $k$ to be the largest possible integer:

\begin{align*}
|p-q| &\leq 4(1) \cdot \pi \\
|p-q| &\leq 12\pi
\end{align*}

This tells us that the arguments of any two points on the curve, which have the smallest possible difference, differ by at most $12\

